<p style="text-align:justify;">amongst the Pines, is found in its greatest perfection on the rocky sides of hills<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Service tree never arrives to any height or perfection<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The Elm seeks low, rich Soils, and the Beech is always found on the skirts of Mountains in black moulds, or else loams.  The choke cherry never rises above 15 or 20 feet &#8211; there is another species of cherry which rises somewhat higher; the fruit is no larger than duckshot but of an agreeable acid.  The large wild red plums and several species of the Haw are found in dry stony soils.  The little Pear is rather a shrub than a tree, as it seldoms exceeds 10 or 12 feet: on dry sandy soils, where the fruit is richest and best, it is rarely more than 2 or 3 feet high &#8211; the fruit resembles a pear in its shape but in nothing else, being in reality a berry: when ripe it is of a deep purple colour and of a delicious taste.  The birds and insects are so fond of it, that it is difficult to get it ripe.  Poplars grow</p>

